WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.120 --> 00:00:06.200
With roughly 1230 kilometers from the melting snow&nbsp;
masses of the alps to the Southern Bight in the

00:00:06.200 --> 00:00:11.000
North Sea, the Rhine River is the economic spine&nbsp;
of western Europe and connects the landlocked

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:15.400
alpine republics through Germany, France and&nbsp;
the Netherlands to the rest of the world.

00:00:15.400 --> 00:00:19.160
Along this path, the river undergoes&nbsp;
6 distinct geographic phases,

00:00:19.160 --> 00:00:23.440
starting with the Alpine Rhine in southern&nbsp;
Switzerland, which forms from many smaller

00:00:23.440 --> 00:00:28.400
mountain creeks whose milky waters eventually&nbsp;
combine into the Anterior and Posterior Rhine.

00:00:28.400 --> 00:00:31.480
After about 100 kilometers the river becomes an important border

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:36.440
marker, separating Switzerland from Liechtenstein&nbsp;
and Austria, before collecting in Lake Constance.

00:00:36.440 --> 00:00:40.280
Despite the 200 kilometer long journey&nbsp;
that these waters have already traveled,

00:00:40.280 --> 00:00:45.640
for navigational purposes, it is here where the&nbsp;
river officially starts. The Old Rhine Bridge

00:00:45.640 --> 00:00:51.120
in the city of Constance marks the 0 km datum&nbsp;
for the Rhinekilometer scale and as the Rhine

00:00:51.120 --> 00:00:55.040
winds its way through the hard limestone&nbsp;
rock of the Swiss-German border frontier,

00:00:55.040 --> 00:01:00.040
its persistence in an ever changing topography&nbsp;
shows in the form of the Rhine Falls, the most

00:01:00.040 --> 00:01:04.560
powerful waterfall of Europe. In just&nbsp;
15.000 years since the last ice age,

00:01:04.560 --> 00:01:09.920
the river eroded away the rock which blocked its&nbsp;
path, creating this fascinating natural spectacle.

00:01:09.920 --> 00:01:13.520
Towards the end of its journey through&nbsp;
Switzerland, the Rhine turns sharply

00:01:13.520 --> 00:01:17.600
at Basel's "Rhine knee," passing the&nbsp;
Switzerland-France-Germany tripoint

00:01:17.600 --> 00:01:22.680
border. The narrow and rapid river here has&nbsp;
long hindered access to landlocked Switzerland,

00:01:22.680 --> 00:01:28.880
so France built the 50km Grand Canal d'Alsace,&nbsp;
which is a parallel waterway that tames the Rhine,

00:01:28.880 --> 00:01:34.240
and enables navigation to Switzerland and hydropower&nbsp;
extraction for France's industrial heartland.

00:01:34.240 --> 00:01:38.800
Roughly half-way along its course and entirely&nbsp;
within Germany now, the largest tributary,

00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:43.840
the River Main confluences on the eastern bank,&nbsp;
which also acts as a gateway for inter-european

00:01:43.840 --> 00:01:49.400
ship traffic, connecting to the Danube and the&nbsp;
Black Sea through a series of locks and canals.

00:01:49.400 --> 00:01:54.400
Past this point, the Middle Rhine impresses&nbsp;
with over 50 pompous medieval castles and

00:01:54.400 --> 00:02:00.080
terraced vineyards covering the hills and rocky&nbsp;
out-crops of its banks, turning the Rhine into a

00:02:00.080 --> 00:02:04.920
fairytale land. The up to 200 meter deep&nbsp;
Rhine gorge walls in this section slowly

00:02:04.920 --> 00:02:08.520
give way to more mellow banks again,&nbsp;
with the urban centers of Germany's

00:02:08.520 --> 00:02:12.520
most populous and most productive&nbsp;
region replacing the tranquility.

00:02:12.520 --> 00:02:18.200
Over 10.5 million people call this short stretch&nbsp;
their home, and with most of the major tributaries

00:02:18.200 --> 00:02:23.240
having now combined their water masses, the Rhine&nbsp;
has turned into a slow flowing giant that meanders

00:02:23.240 --> 00:02:29.440
through the flat German and Dutch countryside.&nbsp;
200 km before the delta, the river only lies 15m

00:02:29.440 --> 00:02:34.360
above the water level of the North Sea, and the&nbsp;
mellow gradient leads to the main stem fanning

00:02:34.360 --> 00:02:39.120
out and covering nearly the entire southern part&nbsp;
of the Netherlands. These broad, interconnected

00:02:39.120 --> 00:02:43.880
waterways create ideal conditions for the shipping&nbsp;
industry, which has established itself across the

00:02:43.880 --> 00:02:49.000
delta streams, with Europe's busiest&nbsp;
port, lying right at the gateway to the North Sea.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:52.720
If you want to learn more about the world’s&nbsp;
greatest river, you can check out this playlist,

00:02:52.720 --> 00:02:55.440
where I have already covered many&nbsp;
of the world’s longest rivers,

00:02:55.440 --> 00:02:59.000
or watch what YouTube thinks is best for&nbsp;
you here. See you in the next one, cheers.

